Machine Learning Engineer Nanodegree¶

Capstone Project¶

As described in my proposal [1] that for this project I am going to replicate a study [2] that try use a bench martk facial dataset to predict the attractiveness consistent with human perceptions.

I am trying to replicate the study and later will use the model to create a mobile app to assign a as score in real time.

In my solution I am will use ResNet50 as feature extractor and then will try to train a dense layer as a regressor that will be benched marks against Support Vector Regressor

import config

Using TensorFlow backend.

Data Exploration¶

For this project I am relying on the original dataset [3] of 5500 face images (Asians and Caucasian male/female). Every face has given a score between 0-5 of perceived attractiveness. All images are 350x350 in shape. Out of 5500 images 4000 faces are Asian(male/female) so it would be interesting at least anecdotally to see the effect on other faces not represented in the dataset.

Here I am showing an example from the orginal paper that shows how the dataset is actually distributed.

In [36]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

feature_file = config.FBP5500_SOURCE+"/train_test_files/All_labels.txt"
#Process feature dictionary
feature_dict = {}
with open(feature_file) as f:
    for line in f:
        (key, val) = line.split()
        feature_dict[key] = float(val)
        
all_scores = feature_dict.values()
hist, bins = np.histogram(list(all_scores), bins=15)

width = 0.9 * (bins[1] - bins[0])
center = (bins[:-1] + bins[1:]) / 2
plt.bar(center, hist, align='center', width=width)
plt.show()

Above is a simple histogram of the scores in the original data. This gives us a glimpse of what kind of dataset we have and sort of making sense that majority are regressing to the middle when it comes to attractiveness. It is important to note that there are some celebrity faces in the dataset and that might explain some medium towers around 4.0.

Preprocessing¶

For dataset involging images it's always a good idea to preprocess, extract feature and serialize. This step will result in faster training time later. It would be much easier to crate custom generator later.

dataprocessor.py in the source folder provide these utility methods. I am loading a batch of image, extracting features using ResNet50 and storing them into HDF5 file along with associated features.

Once completed all 5500x350x350x3tensors will be saved as 5500x2048 features map in ./output/FaceDB.hd5f file. These featuers are the output of the RestNet50 imagenet dataset.

Baseline¶

For establishing baseline I am using sklearn.svm.SVR. Since we have already extracted features so we can run it pretty quicly on a relative small dataset.

The loss function as I mentioned earlier will be Mean Squared Error for our baseline and propsosed solution. It's the same old trusted function and can be described as

In [4]:
from sklearn.svm import SVR
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import h5py
import numpy as np
from sklearn.metrics import regression

reg = SVR(kernel="rbf")
f = h5py.File(config.DATABSE_FILE, "r")

features = np.array(f["features"])
labels = np.array(f["labels"])

trainX, testX, trainY, testY = train_test_split(features, labels, test_size=0.1, shuffle=True)
reg.fit(trainX, trainY)

print("[INFO] Baseline Score (MSE) {}".format(regression.mean_squared_error(testY, reg.predict(testX))))

[INFO] Baseline Score (MSE) 0.03216202614243425

Proposed model.¶

We are just adding a dense layer on top fo the extracted features for simple regression. After running the ResNet feature extractor this problem has become very simple.

I am also using 90/10 split for traing and testing. The only differnce is the 10% data is used as validation date during training. Notice how fast the training is due to the fact that the hard part has already been taking care of. I am using Titan XP for training.

Anecdotal proof and visual reassurance¶

Below is a grid of some personal, friends, random folks and celebrity photos. Model seems to be assigning high scores to celebrities and regressing back to mean when it comes to normal faces. In some cases I tried to stylize and was able to get some good score.

Note that how Angelina Jolie, Julia Roberts and Idris Elba's face got high score although there were no black faces in the dataset.

In [13]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid import ImageGrid
%matplotlib inline
import numpy as np
import cv2
from math import ceil

scores = scores.reshape((1,-1))[0]

plt.style.use('seaborn-bright')
fig = plt.figure(1, (15., 15.))
grid = ImageGrid(fig, 111,  # similar to subplot(111)
                 nrows_ncols=(ceil(len(image_files)/6), 6),  # creates 2x2 grid of axes
                 axes_pad=0.1,  # pad between axes in inch.
                 )

font = cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_DUPLEX
for i, file in enumerate(image_files):
    im = cv2.cvtColor(cv2.imread(file), cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    cv2.putText(im, str(scores[i]), (10, 50), font, 1.5, (255,0,0), 2)
    grid[i].imshow(im)  # The AxesGrid object work as a list of axes.

plt.show()

iOS App¶

Note: The iPhone application source was also uploaded in the project repo [4]

Rather than providing a score I am classifying a selfie pose as Low, GOOD and Awesome. The idea is to help people capture best faces when the beholder agent things it looks attractive.

Here's a breakdown of categories
Low < 2.5 2.5 > GOOD < 4.0 Awesome >= 4.0

Here I am pretending to be frowny and happy and getting the treatment from the app accordingly. I run the model every 10 frames so it updates pretty quickly as you adjust faces.
